{"000-section": {"000-title": "Jal Shakti Abhiyan \u2013 National Water Conservation Scheme Launched by Central Govt."}, "001-section": {"000-title": "Central govt. started national water conservation scheme named Jal Shakti Abhiyan, 1st phase to continue from 1 July to 15 September 2019 in 256 districts, farmers to be encouraged to adopt efficient irrigation practices to gradually shift to less water intensive crops", "001-normal": "Table of Contents", "002-listElement": "- Jal Shakti Abhiyan \u2013 National Water Conservation Scheme", "003-listElement": "- Krishi Vigyan Kendras \u2013 Component of Jal Shakti Mission", "004-listElement": "- Implementation of Jal Shakti Water Conservation Scheme", "005-listElement": "- Categories for Water Conservation Strategies", "006-listElement": "- Jal Shakti Scheme Progress Monitoring"}, "002-section": {"000-title": "Jal Shakti Abhiyan \u2013 National Water Conservation Scheme", "001-normal": "India is facing an acute shortage which is likely to get worse, so the govt. has launched Jal Shakti Abhiyan. This countrywide water conservation scheme focuses on 256 districts and 1,592 blocks with lowest groundwater availability. Around half of the country is stressed with water. So, there is a need to start jan andolan (mass movement) in order to ensure that we can conserve water for future generations.", "002-normal": "Till date, Indian people are able to save only 8% of rainwater which is quite low. We must enhance our capabilities to store rain water through rainwater harvesting. India\u2019s per capita water availability has reduced from 1,816 cubic metres in 2001 to 1,545 cubic metres in 2011. Upto 2025, this per capita water availability is expected to further get reduced to 1,345 cubic metres.", "003-normal": "Most of the districts with over exploitation of groundwater are present in the states of Rajasthan (29), Tamil Nadu (27) and Telangana (24)."}, "003-section": {"000-title": "Krishi Vigyan Kendras \u2013 Component of Jal Shakti Mission", "001-normal": "The central govt. will also mobilize farmers through Krishi Vigyan Kendras and urges them to make a shift to efficient irrigation practices. Around 89% of water is used for irrigation in India, which is 3 to 5 times more as compared to other countries like China. So, there is a need to shift to less water-intensive crops and recharge our aquifers. One such initiative is started in Haryana where farmers are given financial incentives to shift from paddy to maize cultivation."}, "004-section": {"000-title": "Implementation of Jal Shakti Water Conservation Scheme", "001-normal": "Each district is going to draft a water conservation plan with main focus on rainwater harvesting. All the nodal officers will work with urban local bodies (ULBs) for reuse of waste water for industrial and agricultural use. This Jal Shakti Mission will include segregation of grey water (kitchen) and black water (sewarage). Each of urban areas will restore at least one traditional water body."}, "005-section": {"000-title": "Categories for Water Conservation Strategies", "001-normal": "All the water conservation strategies will fall under 5 categories:-", "002-listElement": "- Rainwater harvesting", "003-listElement": "- Renovation of traditional water bodies and tanks", "004-listElement": "- Reuse of water and recharge structures", "005-listElement": "- Watershed development", "006-listElement": "- Intensive afforestation", "007-normal": "All the activities would be carried out under the Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Scheme.  \n **Also Read** \u2013 [PM Nal Se Jal Scheme \u2013 Jal Jivan Mission](https://sarkariyojana.com/pm-nal-se-jal-scheme-piped-water-supply-jal-jivan-mission/)"}, "006-section": {"000-title": "Jal Shakti Scheme Progress Monitoring", "001-normal": "The progress of the Jal Shakti scheme would be monitored by a nodal officer who could be either an additional or joint secretary in each district. As India is facing one of its worst water crisis and various states are facing drought like conditions, so govt. has come up with Jal Shakti Water Conservation Scheme. This situation is worsened after delayed onset and weak progress of southwest monsoon providing 75% of India\u2019s annual rainfall.", "002-normal": "Till date, India is facing rainfall deficit of 33% with Tamil Nadu, Telangana, Andhra Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh, Bihar and Jharkhand facing deficit of more than 20%. The water levels in reservoirs is lowered following scanty rains. Moreover, the total \u201clive storage\u201d available in 91 major reservoirs maintained by the Central Water Commission has dropped from 17% to 16% of capacity (161.9 BCM). This is less than the amount which was present during the corresponding period in 2018.", "003-normal": "Source / Reference Link: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/jal-shakti-abhiyan-govt-launches-water-conservation-campaign/articleshow/70026830.cms"}}